    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-05-28T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-05-28T11:00:00-05:00" n="395"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d395">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 P.W./5–2846: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-05-28T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 28, 1946—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 28—6:21 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1678. I saw Molotov this afternoon and raised the question of the Pauley Mission.
                    He informed me that Pauley and his party had <pb facs="0537" n="525"
                        xml:id="pg_525"/> already arrived in Northern Korea,<note n="52"
                        xml:id="d395fn1">The Department in its telegram 984, May 28, 8 p.m., to
                        Moscow, quoted Mr. Pauley as reporting his party of 26 (10 principals, 2
                        aides, 5 interpreters, 3 secretaries, 1 train chief, 1 surgeon, and 4
                        drivers) expected to leave May 29 at 7 a.m. for north Korea (740.00119
                        P.W./5–2846).</note> but he declined to agree officially to any modification
                    of the original time limit. I gathered from his remarks that the Foreign Office
                    attitude is a reflection of irritation in the Soviet Army which obviously has
                    been objecting to the Pauley Mission, and that the original concession was about
                    as far as Foreign Office could go. I am of the opinion that Mr. Pauley will be
                    given his minimum of 5 days for visiting plants and economic facilities.</p>
                <p>Department please repeat to Tokyo as 47 and Seoul.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
